So programming has three fundamental pillars: 
  1. Language 
  2. Logic 
  3. Domain 

Python was a Christmas project of a man named Guido van Rossum who was from Amsterdam. He started developing it in 1980s and 0.9.0 version of it was released in 1989.
The current version of Python is 3.14.5    Version number consists of Major.Minor.Micro 
Major = Any major changes in the language itself 
Minor = Minor changes in the language
Micro = bug fixes/patches

Python is not a programming language, it is nothing but set of rules. Below are few listed types of python: 
  1. Cpython (C) ~ everyone uses this
  2. Jython (Java)
  3. pypy (Python)
  4. ironpython (C#)

Features of python: 
1. Simple 
2. Platform independent 
3. Architecture Neutral 
4. Extensive libraries 
5. Dynamic typing 
6. Virtual Language as its based off of PVM (Python Virtual Machine) [Native languages are C,cpp]
7. Open Source 

First the source code is taken into compiler which converts it into byte code (pyc format in python) which is then interpreted by the interpreter into machine language i.e. binay.

[ Source Code (.py) ] ──> ( Lexical analysis, parsing, Compilation Step )  ──> [ Bytecode (.pyc) ] ──> ( Python Virtual Machine ) ──> [ CPU Execution ]
